<span id="iv.vi.ii.lxvii"></span>

<span id="iv.vi.ii.lxvii-p1"></span> <span class="c11"><span
id="iv.vi.ii.lxvii-p1.1"></span>Chapter LXVII</span>.—*That Religion
began in the East.*

<span id="iv.vi.ii.lxvii-p2"></span>“<span class="c13"><span
id="iv.vi.ii.lxvii-p2.1"></span>For</span> since the power of Divine
light, and the law of sacred worship, which, proceeding in the first
instance, through the favor of God, from the bosom, as it were, of the
East, have illumined the world, by their sacred radiance, I naturally
believed that you would be the first to promote the salvation of other
nations, and resolved with all energy of thought and diligence of
enquiry to seek your aid. As soon, therefore, as I had secured my
decisive victory and unquestionable triumph over my enemies, my first
enquiry was concerning that object which I felt to be of paramount
interest and importance.

